Contact the Elderly | About Us | Baillie Gifford



























Contact the Elderly








Contact the Elderly

Each year Baillie Gifford invites staff to nominate a small local charity as its Charity of the Year. Nominations are only accepted for small charities where Baillie Gifford's support will make a real impact on the services they provide. A shortlist is produced, and staff then vote for the charity they would like the firm to support.
The chosen charity for 2015/16 was Contact the Elderly, a local charity dedicated to tackling loneliness and isolation among older people.
The backbone of Contact the Elderly is its volunteers, who host the tea parties and drive the elderly to and from each event. This includes a number of staff from Baillie Gifford, some of whom spoke about their experience of volunteering for the charity
















You can tell that these parties mean so much to the guests and it’s something they clearly look forward to.






Hannah Dobson – Compliance Analyst
“I was really nervous when I picked up my guests for the first time, but I had no need to be. We had lots to chat about and there was so much laughter – it was like we had known each other for years.
“It’s fantastic to see the older guests connect with each other. In fact, two of the ladies I pick up went to school together and hadn’t seen each other for around 75 years until they attended the same tea party. They still recognised each other after all that time and they instantly connected over past friendship.
“You can tell that these parties mean so much to the guests and it’s something they clearly look forward to.”
Tracey Squires – Compliance Policies and Training Co-ordinator
“I have wanted to volunteer for a long time, but I struggled to find something that wasn’t too time intensive. Since the Contact the Elderly tea parties only take place once a month, it’s perfect for me as it’s not too much of a time commitment.
“The older people love telling us stories from their youth, and last week when I was in the car with one of the guests, we drove past the church where she got married in 1948. It’s a real honour to be in the company of people who have done so much in their lives.
“We are all going to get older and it’s nice to know that Contact the Elderly is there, looking out for us and our loved ones. I think that’s why the charity resonates with so many people.”
Jessie Wilson – Client Service Manager
“I’ve only recently become a driver for Contact the Elderly. Lack of free time previously held me back from volunteering but being a driver for the charity only involves a few hours once a month.
“It’s been amazing to see the elderly guests get out of the house and be in the company of a group of people, enjoying some conversation.
“I find volunteering for Contact the Elderly very enjoyable, so it doesn’t feel like I’m going out of my way to help people. It has given me the opportunity to meet some lovely people, who have great life stories, all while I get to enjoy eating some cake, too!”
Máirín Eydmann – Project Manager
“I was part of the Baillie Gifford Habitat for Humanity team last year, which was a great experience. I really enjoyed going to Ethiopia and working with the local community. The experience made me want to seek out an opportunity to work with my local community in Edinburgh.
“When I heard that Contact the Elderly was looking for volunteers, it seemed like a good fit for me. I’m a keen baker, so hosting tea parties meant that I could combine my enthusiasm for baking with volunteering.
“I also enjoy socialising with our elderly neighbours, so extending that to tea party guests was the natural thing for me to do. And volunteering for Contact the Elderly is no hardship. I get to have great conversations with the group and eat cake. It’s a fantastic way to spend a Sunday afternoon.”
Dorothy Green – Receptionist
“I had been thinking about volunteering for a while, so when Contact the Elderly became our charity of the year, it seemed like the ideal opportunity.
“I’m so glad I got involved with the charity. I am now the driver of a lovely 90-year-old lady and together we go along to a tea party hosted by a Baillie Gifford volunteer, one Sunday each month.
“There are six older ladies in the group along with six Baillie Gifford drivers plus the host and we spend two hours chatting over cups of tea and delicious cakes. The whole process is very rewarding, and above all enjoyable. I would thoroughly recommend it to anyone who might be considering volunteering.”
Sarah Mitchell – Investment Assistant
“I was keen to get involved in some charity work in my local area when I heard about Contact the Elderly through Baillie Gifford.
“I’m a volunteer driver for a lovely lady, who is 98 years old. She had a great time at the tea party, which got her out of the house and gave her the chance to meet new people. I also really enjoyed chatting to her and hearing more about her life.
“My first tea party was great – it’s nice to spend an afternoon listening to the group’s stories. I’m already looking forward to my next tea party.”












